<h4 class="likesubsectionHead" id="sa-static-code-analysis" style="margin: 0; padding: 0; box-sizing: border-box; margin-top: 1.5em; margin-bottom: 0.5em; color: #222; font-weight: 600;"><a id="x1-3000" style="margin: 0; padding: 0; box-sizing: border-box; color: #667eea; text-decoration: none; transition: color 0.3s ease;"></a>SA-11(1): Static Code Analysis</h4>
<!-- l. 27 --><p class="noindent" style="margin: 0; padding: 0; box-sizing: border-box; margin-bottom: 1em;">Most static analysis tools would be able to identify the issue in the code. Making sure that Static Application
Security Testing (SAST) is enabled and enforcing is a good, easy first-line of defense. Using the static code analysis
tool <span class="ec-lmtt-10" style="margin: 0; padding: 0; box-sizing: border-box;">infer</span>, the issue is detected in Listing <a href="#x1-3001r2" style="margin: 0; padding: 0; box-sizing: border-box; color: #667eea; text-decoration: none; transition: color 0.3s ease;">2<!-- tex4ht:ref: lst:20250127:sast  --></a>.
</p>   
